This study examines how eighteen teachers' participation in a Texas-based Research-Practice Partnership (RPP) impacted their pedagogical capacity to shape students' access to, participation in, and experiences within computer science education (CSEd). Teachers engaged in comprehensive professional development (PD) that included content knowledge training, innovative pedagogy courses, and collaborative workshops. Data collection included semi-structured interviews collected after year two of teacher participation in the program, and interviews were analyzed using thematic analysis combining deductive coding based on the CAPE framework (Fletcher & Warner, 2021) with inductive analysis of emerging themes. Findings revealed that the RPP helped teachers expand conceptions of access beyond course availability to address systemic barriers through intentional recruitment and pipeline creation; developed specific strategies ensuring increased participation by monitoring classroom demographics and using varied participation methods; and created relevant experiences by integrating students' lived contexts and leveraging the participants own authentic identities as pedagogy. This research demonstrates how RPPs develop teachers' pedagogical capacity through sustained and relevant PD, revealing that PD translates into teaching practices with appropriate scaffolding and time, ultimately fostering learning environments where all students can thrive in CSEd.